Problem 2

Exploratory Data Analysis – Part 1 – Examining Categorical Variables

  1. (5 points) How many unique values of these two variables (Embarked and Pclass) are there? What are the unique values? Provide a single sentence describing what they actually mean.
unique(titanic$Embarked)
## [1] "S" "C" "Q"
unique(titanic$Pclass)
## [1] 3 1 2

There are 3 unique values for each variable. The Embarked values represent the port of embarkment and the PClass values represent the ticket classes.

  1. (10 points) How many of each unique value are there? To find this out, use the following approach, which counts the number of times each category appears in a vector:
titanic %>%
  group_by(Embarked) %>%
  summarize(count = n())
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   Embarked count
##   <chr>    <int>
## 1 C          130
## 2 Q           28
## 3 S          554
titanic %>%
  group_by(Pclass) %>%
  summarize(count = n())
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   Pclass count
##    <int> <int>
## 1      1   184
## 2      2   173
## 3      3   355

Problem 3

(5 points each)

Exploratory Data Analysis – Part 2 – Visualizing Cateogical Variables

  1. Create a bar chart that shows the distribution of the number of individuals that Embarked at each specific port as mentioned in our titanic dataset. The x-axis should show the unique Embarkeds. The y-axis should show the number of passengers that embarked at each port. To do this, create a base plot with: Embarked_dist_plot <- ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)). Then type Embarked_dist_plot + geom_bar() + coord_cartesian().
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar() +
    coord_cartesian()

  1. That graph is okay, but let’s add a little color. Recall that, the color used to “fill” the bars is one of the “aesthetics” of the graph that we can specify. So, all we need to do is add the color aesthetic to our previous command: Embarked_dist_plot + geom_bar(aes(fill = Embarked)) + coord_cartesian(). (This will fill the bars in with different colors corresponding to each unique Embarked.) Notice that ggplot adds a legend to our plot automatically. We’ll learn about how to specify different colors on a future assignment. That said, feel free to look up how to do this and change the color scheme here!
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill = Embarked)) +
    coord_cartesian()

  1. Recall that aesthetics map pieces of the data to parts of the graph. In part (b) above, we mapped the Embarked variable to fill color (fill) of the bars in our bar chart using the aes() function. We can also fill the bars with a single color, since the colors here aren’t necessary. Here, since the color “blue” is not part of the original data, we specify the fill argument outside of the aes() function, since we’re not mapping a piece of the data to a part of the graph: Embarked_dist_plot + geom_bar(fill = "blue") + coord_cartesian().
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar(fill = "blue") +
    coord_cartesian()

  1. Okay, our graph is looking a bit better – but we’re still missing a title! Add a title to our plot with the labs() function as we did in a previous assignment. Be sure that your title uses proper capitalization, is succinct, and provides a brief description of what the graph shows. Feel free to also add a subtitle and a caption if you’d like, but be sure that these are informative.
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar(fill = "blue") +
    coord_cartesian() +
    labs(title = "Counts of passengers by port of embarkment")

  1. The graph already has some x- and y-axis labels, but they’re kind of boring. How does ggplot choose the default labels?

It chooses the default labels using variable names, or the statistic name if applicable.

  1. Let’s change the labels. Update the labs() function to do this, adding it to the code for your graph as you did with the title. Use the help documentation for the labs() function to figure out how it works. (Hint: Specify the x and y arguments.) Be sure that your labels describe what is being displayed on each axis. Recall what the descriptions of the variables here.
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar(fill = "blue") +
    coord_cartesian() +
    labs(title = "Counts of Passengers by Port of Embarkation",
         x = "Port of Embarkation",
         y = "Number of Passengers")

  1. Okay, now we have a pretty nice graph. Let’s describe it for someone who isn’t as familiar with the data as we are. Describe the distribution you see in your bar chart. Which port did the most passengers embark on? Which port had the fewest passengers embark on? From the graph, roughly how many people embarked at Southampton?

Most passengers embarked at Southampton, while the least embarked at Queenstown. Almost 600 people embarked at Southampton.

  1. In part (a) (and throughout our ever-growing line of code to create this graphic), + coord_cartesian() tells ggplot to make this plot in the cartesian (x-y) plane. What would happen if we used a different coordinate system? Try changing coord_cartesian() to coord_polar() (present this graphic only). Be sure to adjust the title and axis labels as necessary. What happens? This is called a rose diagram.
ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Embarked)) +
    geom_bar(fill = "blue") +
    coord_polar() +
    labs(title = "Counts of Passengers by Port of Embarkation",
         x = "Port of Embarkation",
         y = "Number of Passengers")

  1. Which graph do you like better – the graph in (h), or the graph in (g)? There is not necessarily a right answer here (yet); just be sure to justify your choice. Which graph is easier to read? In which graph is it easier to discern the differences amongst the categories? In which graph is it easier to estimate the exact number of passengers that embarked at the different ports?

The graph in (g) as it is easier to read. It is easier to compare the differences in counts in (g) than in (h). It is also easier to tell the number of passengers at each port in (g) as it is easier to read off the y-axis ticks than trying to follow the radial components in (h).

  1. (12 points) Create a bar chart that shows the distribution of the Pclass variable in our titanic dataset. The x-axis should show the unique values of Pclass. The y-axis should show the overall frequency of that passenger class in the dataset. Use a single color for all sentiments. Give the graph an appropriate title and appropriate x- and y-axis labels. 2-Dimensional Categorical Data

Next week, we’ll cover the visualization of 2-dimensional categorical data. If you’re feeling ambitious, however, you can try to do this with our Embarked and Pclass variables here.

Re-create the graph from problem 3, part (f), except instead of giving each bar the same blue fill, fill in each passenger class’ bar with multiple colors – proportional to the frequency of which of the three ports these passengers embarked.

Hint: This is easier to do than it sounds with ggplot. You need to map a piece of the data (Pclass) to a piece of the graph (the fill color of the bars).

Note: The instructor and TAs are not allowed to help you with bonus problems!

ggplot(data = titanic, aes(x = Pclass)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill = Embarked)) +
    coord_cartesian() +
    labs(title = "Counts of Passengers by Port of Embarkation and Ticket Class",
         x = "Ticket Class",
         y = "Number of Passengers")
